==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Punt
<hw>Punt</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>ponter</ets>,
or It. <ets>puntare</ets>, fr. L. <ets>punctum</ets> point. See
<er>Point</er>.]</ety> <def>To play at basset, baccara, faro. or omber;
to gamble.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She heard . . . of his <qex>punting</qex> at gaming tables.</q>
<rj><qau>Thackeray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Punt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Punt
<hw>Punt</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Act of playing at basset, baccara,
faro, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Punt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Punt
<hw>Punt</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS., fr. L. <ets>ponto</ets> punt,
pontoon. See <er>Pontoon</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A
flat-bottomed boat with square ends. It is adapted for use in shallow
waters.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Punt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Punt
<hw>Punt</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To propel, as a boat in
shallow water, by pushing with a pole against the bottom; to push or
propel (anything) with exertion.</def>
<rj><au>Livingstone.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Football)</fld> <def>To kick (the ball) before it
touches the ground, when let fall from the hands.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Punt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Punt
<hw>Punt</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Football)</fld> <def>The act of
punting the ball.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Punt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Punt
<hw>Punt</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To boat or hunt in a
punt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To punt a football.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Puntello</ent>⟦br⟧
